what does the whole nine yards mean what is the origin of this phrase the whole nine yard means everything that is relevant the whole thing for example he decided to take everything to college his books his stereo his computer his skis the whole nine yards the source of this expression is not known but there are several possibilities the amount of cloth required to make a complete suit of clothes the fully set sails of a three masted ship where each mast carries three yards that is spars to support the sails or the amount of cement in cubic yards contained in a cement mixer for a big construction job colloquial origin one of the most common theories of the phrase's origin is that the expression dates from the second world war where nine yards was the length of an aircraft machine gun ammunition belt and to go the full nine yards was to use it up entirely the expression however has been reliably dated back only to early in u s air force slang recorded in vietnam by november it was recorded in use in the u s army likewise from vietnam and by mid was appearing in newspaper advertisements in the united states the first citation in the oxford english dictionary is from in the magazine word watching Rigging M60 machine gun USS Walke (DD-723) Slang USS Yorktown (CV-10) Machine gun American and British English differences USS Enterprise (CV-6) Chinese language M16 (rifle) Battleship Sailing USS Alfred A. Cunningham (DD-752) Ammunition USS Arizona (BB-39) United States Marine Corps USS San Francisco (CA-38) Concrete Rail terminology Ton Chinese character Glossary of nautical terms Marathon (computer game) USS Arnold J. Isbell (DD-869) USS New Jersey (BB-62) Ship USS Pennsylvania (BB-38) USS Hancock (CV-19) USS Wadsworth (DD-516) USS Albemarle (AV-5) United States Navy Yardarm Shit Panama Canal Locks USS O'Bannon (DD-450) Apple Macintosh Dictionary Wolfenstein: Enemy Territory HMS Electra (H27) Anti-aircraft warfare USS Valley Forge (CV-45) Brigantine Panama Canal USS Helena 